WEBVTT

00:05.421 --> 00:07.822
(sirens wailing in distance)

00:12.461 --> 00:14.829
(explosions in distance)

00:20.135 --> 00:21.770
(alarm beeping)

00:21.771 --> 00:23.138
(alarm stops)

00:23.139 --> 00:25.539
(gunfire in distance)

00:27.476 --> 00:30.479
(indistinct shouting)

00:30.480 --> 00:32.414
(gunfire continues)

00:32.415 --> 00:35.818
MAN: You're off to a good start.

00:35.819 --> 00:37.986
(gunfire continues over TV)

00:37.987 --> 00:40.689
Jason, why don't you turn that off now?

00:40.690 --> 00:42.758
- Come on, come get some breakfast.
- JASON: All right, let me...

00:42.759 --> 00:44.460
- That's enough carnage for 7:00 a.m.
- All right, let me save it.

00:44.461 --> 00:45.594
- Hold on.
- Uh, oh, I'll save it for you.

00:45.595 --> 00:46.695
JASON: Well...

00:46.696 --> 00:47.863
Dad... come on.

00:47.864 --> 00:49.398
(laughs) Come on, let's go.

00:49.399 --> 00:51.266
Hey, don't act like you got
some big problem with my game.

00:51.267 --> 00:52.367
You play it, too. Okay.

00:52.368 --> 00:53.969
- Aah!
- Oh, come on!

00:53.970 --> 00:55.237
- Breakfast.
- Oh.

00:55.238 --> 00:57.072
The discovery of hypocrisy.

00:57.073 --> 01:00.242
Bitter moment in any young
revolutionary's life.

01:00.243 --> 01:02.344
Well, kid's got a point, but,
uh, when he's not telling me

01:02.345 --> 01:03.912
how much I suck at
this game, he actually

01:03.913 --> 01:05.480
sometimes tells me
something about his life.

01:05.482 --> 01:07.783
- Right.
- Hey, you okay?

01:07.784 --> 01:09.284
Yeah, I'm good.

01:09.285 --> 01:11.353
'Cause you've been just going nonstop

01:11.354 --> 01:12.821
since you got back from Iran.

01:12.822 --> 01:15.157
Oh, I'm a little jetlagged
still, but I'm good.

01:15.158 --> 01:16.191
I'm fine.

01:16.192 --> 01:19.128
Promise.

01:19.129 --> 01:21.430
I'm just saying, going
back to school is gonna be

01:21.431 --> 01:23.398
a big adjustment after
lying around here all day,

01:23.399 --> 01:24.733
- playing video games.
- Yeah.

01:24.734 --> 01:26.401
Yeah, you should know, dropout.

01:26.402 --> 01:28.403
- Oh, burn!
- Ooh!

01:28.404 --> 01:29.274
Good comeback, Padawan.

01:29.275 --> 01:30.906
ALISON: You know that
if you get kicked out

01:30.907 --> 01:31.671
of two schools in a row,

01:31.672 --> 01:33.242
you have to go to
military school, right?

01:33.243 --> 01:34.443
It's, like, the law.

01:34.444 --> 01:35.878
- Hey, I could handle military school.
- Yeah, right.

01:35.879 --> 01:37.741
Okay, wait. What about,
uh, home-schooling, pal?

01:37.742 --> 01:38.680
Uh, I'll stick with public school.

01:38.681 --> 01:40.449
Oh, come on. Just
think of it. You and me

01:40.450 --> 01:42.784
studying all these great books,

01:42.785 --> 01:44.386
spending hours having
philosophical discussions.

01:44.387 --> 01:45.521
Mm. Shoot me now.

01:45.522 --> 01:46.288
Jason.

01:46.289 --> 01:48.089
JASON: What did I say?

01:49.558 --> 01:52.728
Well, I'm-I'm glad that you're
on board with public school,

01:52.729 --> 01:54.563
because that is where you're going.

01:54.564 --> 01:57.166
Oh, we have that-that,
uh, orientation meeting

01:57.167 --> 01:58.667
- at 11:00, okay?
- Yeah, I know.

01:58.668 --> 02:00.636
Listen, um, I cleared my
schedule out this morning.

02:00.637 --> 02:02.337
You want to take the time off?
Maybe we can go...

02:02.338 --> 02:03.605
I can't. I've got meetings.

02:03.606 --> 02:04.706
Then I've got

02:04.707 --> 02:07.342
meetings after those
meetings, so I got to go.

02:07.343 --> 02:08.810
- Bye, guys.
- ALISON: Bye, Mom.

02:08.811 --> 02:10.179
- Love you.
- STEVIE: Bye, Mom. Love you.

02:10.180 --> 02:11.246
Bye. Ow.

02:11.247 --> 02:12.414
- Nice sensitivity, dumb-ass.
- What...? Dad!

02:12.415 --> 02:13.916
Okay, cut it out, both of you.

02:13.917 --> 02:16.618
NADINE: <i>The desk officer
is waiting to brief you</i>

02:16.619 --> 02:17.753
on your first meeting.

02:17.754 --> 02:19.555
- Ecuador?
- Yes, ma'am.

02:19.556 --> 02:21.757
And Matt and Daisy are here

02:21.758 --> 02:23.625
to have a word with you this morning.

02:23.626 --> 02:25.060
Yes, I'm getting that.

02:25.061 --> 02:26.795
Ma'am, we need to prep you
for <i>Face The Nation.</i>

02:26.796 --> 02:27.963
Can't this morning.

02:27.964 --> 02:29.665
I got a thing at my son's school.

02:29.666 --> 02:31.767
Well, you've been at the center
of everything that's happened.

02:31.768 --> 02:33.802
Unearthing Director Munsey's plot,

02:33.803 --> 02:35.037
thwarting the coup in Iran.

02:35.038 --> 02:36.672
The White House wants
you front and center

02:36.673 --> 02:38.440
to reassure the public
that everything is okay.

02:38.441 --> 02:40.809
- Well, is it? News to me.
- This...

02:40.810 --> 02:44.346
The point is, ma'am, I mean,
if there's a hero in this story,

02:44.347 --> 02:46.048
- it's you.
- What did you just say?

02:46.049 --> 02:47.649
Because what I thought

02:47.650 --> 02:50.219
you said is that I'm the
hero of this story?

02:50.220 --> 02:51.853
Excuse me, ma'am. Daisy
didn't mean to imply...

02:51.854 --> 02:53.288
Excuse me, Nadine.

02:53.289 --> 02:55.591
See, what's confusing

02:55.592 --> 02:58.126
is how you could possibly
say something like that,

02:58.127 --> 03:01.630
just days after you attended
Fred Cole's funeral.

03:01.631 --> 03:04.800
Man who literally threw
himself in front of bullets

03:04.801 --> 03:06.368
to save me.

03:06.369 --> 03:09.338
Which is the very definition of heroism.

03:09.339 --> 03:11.073
You come at me with this

03:11.074 --> 03:14.476
win-the-cycle crap again,
it'll be the last time you do.

03:14.477 --> 03:16.211
You understand?

03:16.212 --> 03:19.180
- Yes.
- Yes, ma'am.

03:20.816 --> 03:23.952
Why is there a nurse in my waiting area?

03:23.953 --> 03:25.954
Oh, she's here to follow up

03:25.955 --> 03:27.856
on the exam you received at Landstuhl.

03:27.857 --> 03:30.559
You kept rescheduling, so I had
someone from Walter Reed

03:30.560 --> 03:32.361
- sent over.
- I had said I would go

03:32.362 --> 03:34.296
- to my own doctor when I had time.
- Mm-hmm.

03:34.297 --> 03:36.031
They needed a follow-up ASAP, ma'am.

03:36.032 --> 03:37.299
It's literally doctor's orders.

03:37.300 --> 03:39.334
Et tu, Blake?

03:39.335 --> 03:42.170
NURSE: <i>You're healing
well, Madam Secretary.</i>

03:42.171 --> 03:44.539
Stitches should be ready
to come out in a few days.

03:44.540 --> 03:45.574
Fantastic.

03:45.575 --> 03:47.342
Are you having any pain, ma'am?

03:47.343 --> 03:49.044
Nope. None.

03:49.045 --> 03:51.747
Then, um, I just need
to draw your blood.

03:51.748 --> 03:54.549
Well, I'm on a tight schedule.

03:54.550 --> 03:58.420
I hope you don't mind if I multitask.

03:58.421 --> 04:00.656
So, what does the CEO

04:00.657 --> 04:03.625
of one of America's biggest
oil companies want

04:03.626 --> 04:05.761
from a peon like the Secretary of State?

04:05.762 --> 04:07.429
Chip Harding is here because he believes

04:07.430 --> 04:09.531
you should be doing more
to help Ashmont Petroleum

04:09.532 --> 04:11.333
secure drilling rights in Ecuador,

04:11.334 --> 04:12.467
as opposed to the Chinese.

04:12.468 --> 04:13.602
ELIZABETH: But the proposed

04:13.603 --> 04:15.704
area of the Amazon is highly sensitive,

04:15.705 --> 04:17.539
which is what our desk officer

04:17.540 --> 04:19.341
for the region is here to discuss.

04:19.341 --> 04:20.942
It's Laura, right?

04:20.942 --> 04:22.911
(clears throat) Uh, yes, ma'am.

04:22.912 --> 04:26.448
Let me first say how thrilled
I am to finally meet you in...

04:26.449 --> 04:28.116
person.

04:28.117 --> 04:29.651
Uh,

04:29.652 --> 04:31.486
you okay there, Laura?

04:31.487 --> 04:34.489
Yeah. Just have a little thing about, um...

04:34.490 --> 04:36.525
blood. Um...

04:36.526 --> 04:38.527
- Oh.
- Very sorry, but I'm fine.

04:38.528 --> 04:39.861
Quite all right.

04:39.862 --> 04:41.997
Why don't we just get right to it, then?

04:41.998 --> 04:43.699
Yes, ma'am. As you may have read

04:43.700 --> 04:45.934
in your briefing book, the
Selva Region of eastern Ecuador

04:45.935 --> 04:48.136
is one of the most bio-diverse
areas of the Amazon,

04:48.137 --> 04:49.304
and indeed the world.

04:49.305 --> 04:50.572
MIKE: Home to... count them...

04:50.573 --> 04:53.508
ten primate species,
including the rare Titi monkey.

04:53.509 --> 04:55.577
- There's an image for you.
- LAURA: Developing it

04:55.578 --> 04:57.346
would be extremely damaging to the

04:57.347 --> 05:01.549
local... um... but also...

05:04.319 --> 05:06.988
But also, it is important to remember

05:06.989 --> 05:09.925
that the Amazon is the
world's carbon sink

05:09.926 --> 05:12.527
where much of the CO2
we produce is absorbed

05:12.528 --> 05:14.129
by the trees of...

05:14.130 --> 05:15.397
- Uh-oh.
- Oh, God.

05:15.398 --> 05:17.432
So embarrassed. Excuse me, ma'am.

05:17.433 --> 05:18.867
(mutters)

05:18.868 --> 05:20.402
- Okay.
- MIKE: Hope she makes it

05:20.403 --> 05:22.104
to the porcelain sink in time.

05:22.105 --> 05:24.840
Why don't you go see if she's okay.

05:24.841 --> 05:27.476
Right, the point being, if a
tract this big is developed,

05:27.477 --> 05:31.079
it will speed up the
deforestation process,

05:31.080 --> 05:32.781
which will ultimately lead to what?

05:32.782 --> 05:34.082
Ocean acidification, species die-offs,

05:34.083 --> 05:36.918
larger and more unpredictable
weather events,

05:36.919 --> 05:38.520
increased climate-driven
conflicts and refugees.

05:38.521 --> 05:39.888
You know, your typical

05:39.889 --> 05:41.790
21st century end-of-the-world buffet.

05:41.791 --> 05:42.891
Got it.

05:42.892 --> 05:44.526
LAURA: Sorry. False alarm.

05:44.527 --> 05:47.262
Ma'am, there are more tree
species in a single hectare

05:47.263 --> 05:49.731
of the Selva region than
in all of North America.

05:49.732 --> 05:51.600
If there's a cure for cancer or HIV,

05:51.601 --> 05:52.734
we will probably find it there.

05:52.735 --> 05:54.169
MIKE: Counterpoint.

05:54.170 --> 05:56.505
Chip Harding donates millions
of dollars each election cycle,

05:56.506 --> 05:58.740
which will either be used for or against

05:58.741 --> 05:59.875
your president.

05:59.876 --> 06:01.243
Just something to weigh against

06:01.244 --> 06:02.344
the sad monkeys and magic trees.

06:02.345 --> 06:03.912
And it is part of our job

06:03.913 --> 06:05.080
to promote U.S. businesses abroad,

06:05.081 --> 06:06.815
but if we want to have a
voice in the decision,

06:06.816 --> 06:08.150
we need to act now.

06:08.151 --> 06:09.951
The Ecuadorians are
planning whether to develop

06:09.952 --> 06:11.553
the Selva within a month.

06:11.554 --> 06:13.388
Oh, plenty of time.

06:13.389 --> 06:16.790
All right, why don't we go see
what we can do for Mr. Harding.

06:18.760 --> 06:21.862
Ma'am.

06:22.898 --> 06:25.100
- Oh!
- Oh. Have fun.

06:25.101 --> 06:26.301
I got it. I got it.

06:26.302 --> 06:28.437
Okay. What are you even doing here?

06:28.438 --> 06:29.938
I'm attending your meeting with Chip...

06:29.939 --> 06:31.139
Chip Harding, ma'am.

06:31.140 --> 06:32.941
Okay, isn't Abby about to
go into labor any second?

06:32.942 --> 06:34.676
- Literally any second.
- So, go, go.

06:34.677 --> 06:36.745
I can handle Harding by myself.

06:36.746 --> 06:38.847
If I need more information,
I'll get it from Laura back...

06:38.848 --> 06:40.348
Brilliant, and she really
wanted to make an impression.

06:40.349 --> 06:41.783
Oh, she did. It's all set.

06:41.784 --> 06:43.051
- Go right now.
- Here.

06:43.052 --> 06:44.986
- Okay. There you go.
- Oh, there. Thank you.

06:44.987 --> 06:46.922
Tell Abby to get the epidural early!

06:46.923 --> 06:47.956
You got it!

06:47.957 --> 06:49.591
Key word: early.

06:49.592 --> 06:54.062
Madam Secretary, I'm busy,
and I'm sure you are, too,

06:54.063 --> 06:55.897
so I'll get straight to the point.

06:55.898 --> 06:57.032
I would love it

06:57.033 --> 06:59.501
if the government would
just get out of our way.

06:59.502 --> 07:01.536
Or better yet, help us out for once.

07:01.537 --> 07:02.871
There's a concept.

07:02.872 --> 07:05.006
What is it that you
feel isn't being done

07:05.007 --> 07:06.608
for the oil industry, Mr. Harding?

07:06.609 --> 07:08.610
The SEC and Justice are
breathing down our neck

07:08.611 --> 07:10.779
about the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.

07:10.780 --> 07:13.615
Do take a dim view of bribing
foreign officials, yes.

07:13.616 --> 07:16.017
Come on, you know full
well that that's the way

07:16.018 --> 07:18.053
business gets done in
places like Ecuador.

07:18.054 --> 07:19.588
And let me tell you something.

07:19.589 --> 07:21.089
The Chinese aren't wringing their hands

07:21.090 --> 07:22.257
about doing business.

07:22.258 --> 07:24.125
Given that I can't help
you bribe anybody,

07:24.126 --> 07:26.461
what exactly would you like
the State Department to do?

07:26.462 --> 07:27.596
Offer them aid.

07:27.597 --> 07:29.598
Help in developing vital infrastructure.

07:29.599 --> 07:30.966
We do give them aid.

07:30.967 --> 07:35.303
$218 million last year, to
be exact, but it does come

07:35.304 --> 07:37.739
with anti-corruption
safeguards built in.

07:37.740 --> 07:41.409
So, sorry if that's not helping
you grease the wheels.

07:41.410 --> 07:43.712
Look, the Selva's too
valuable not to be developed.

07:43.713 --> 07:44.913
That's just the facts.

07:44.914 --> 07:46.147
Who do you and the president

07:46.148 --> 07:47.616
prefer to see do it... us or the Chinese?

07:47.617 --> 07:49.017
I guarantee you we care

07:49.018 --> 07:52.420
very deeply about what happens
in the Selva region, and I will

07:52.421 --> 07:54.789
bear your concerns in mind when I meet

07:54.790 --> 07:55.991
with the Ecuadorian ambassador.

07:55.992 --> 07:58.592
Thank you so much for coming in.

08:05.667 --> 08:07.335
A great game is afoot, Madam Secretary,

08:07.336 --> 08:10.872
and we can't win it with one
hand tied behind our back.

08:10.873 --> 08:13.308
I hope the president understands that.

08:13.309 --> 08:15.510
Thank you for your time.

08:15.511 --> 08:18.346
You bet.

08:18.347 --> 08:20.382
Everyone okay?

08:20.383 --> 08:23.418
Well, it's not like we have hurt feelies.

08:23.419 --> 08:25.086
Although, that was quite an outburst.

08:25.087 --> 08:27.022
I understand she's been through a lot,

08:27.023 --> 08:29.682
but the fact is, she needs
to prep for <i>Face the Nation.</i>

08:29.683 --> 08:32.126
I'll try to block out some time in
her schedule for this afternoon.

08:32.128 --> 08:34.195
MATT: It's not like we're
being overly dramatic.

08:34.196 --> 08:35.597
Rogue CIA director

08:35.597 --> 08:37.631
starts a coup in Iran under
the White House's nose?

08:37.633 --> 08:39.534
And the only reason it fails is because

08:39.534 --> 08:41.102
she literally puts herself
in the line of fire.

08:41.102 --> 08:42.804
That's a huge story.

08:42.804 --> 08:43.738
Huge.

08:43.739 --> 08:44.873
I'm aware.

08:44.874 --> 08:45.974
And so is the public, but they haven't

08:45.975 --> 08:47.609
seen her since the
funerals three days ago.

08:47.610 --> 08:50.178
And the longer they don't, the
more she's gonna be pulled

08:50.179 --> 08:51.713
into the morass of suspicion and blame.

08:51.714 --> 08:54.649
She needs to tell her story,
and she can't just wing it.

08:54.650 --> 08:56.418
WOMAN: <i>As it says</i>

08:56.419 --> 08:59.154
in your packet, drop-off is
between 7:30 and 7:50,

08:59.155 --> 09:01.189
but there can be a bit of a
line sometimes, so it's worth

09:01.190 --> 09:03.301
- getting here early.
- HENRY: Maybe if we had a different kid.

09:03.302 --> 09:05.060
(woman laughs)

09:05.061 --> 09:06.661
Well, that covers it.

09:06.662 --> 09:08.163
Welcome to Monroe Junior High.

09:08.164 --> 09:12.434
I'd like to revisit the
security issue if I may.

09:12.435 --> 09:13.802
Uh, of course.

09:13.803 --> 09:16.938
Uh, as I mentioned,

09:16.939 --> 09:18.707
student safety is our
number one priority.

09:18.708 --> 09:20.041
We have two full-time

09:20.042 --> 09:22.811
security officers, metal
detectors at every entrance

09:22.812 --> 09:25.513
and a zero-tolerance policy
on weapons and bullying.

09:25.514 --> 09:28.316
Jason will be in good
hands here, Mrs. McCord.

09:28.317 --> 09:29.451
I'm sure he will be.

09:29.452 --> 09:31.086
ELIZABETH: The thing is, I'm not.

09:31.087 --> 09:33.722
I'd like to provide Jason
with a security detail.

09:33.723 --> 09:35.523
- HENRY: Wait. What?
- No, no.

09:35.524 --> 09:37.359
Nothing obtrusive, just one man.

09:37.360 --> 09:40.295
Given who I am and what I do,
I feel that it's necessary.

09:40.296 --> 09:41.363
Will you

09:41.364 --> 09:42.430
excuse us for one minute?

09:42.431 --> 09:43.598
Absolutely.

09:43.599 --> 09:45.634
Do you want to tell me what's going on?

09:45.635 --> 09:46.935
Just what I said.

09:46.936 --> 09:49.638
I think Jason needs extra security.

09:49.639 --> 09:50.772
Well, the threat assessment guys

09:50.773 --> 09:52.340
at Diplomatic Security
don't think he does.

09:52.341 --> 09:53.875
- Well, I'm their boss.
- Not when it comes

09:53.876 --> 09:55.777
to assigning a security
detail, you're not.

09:55.778 --> 09:58.279
Besides, you said you wanted
Jason to have as normal

09:58.280 --> 10:00.248
a school experience
as possible, as did I.

10:00.249 --> 10:01.383
We settled this.

10:01.384 --> 10:02.984
I am fourth in line for the presidency

10:02.985 --> 10:04.653
of the United States.

10:04.654 --> 10:06.888
He doesn't get to be a normal child.

10:06.889 --> 10:09.190
Okay. Is this about
what happened in Iran?

10:09.191 --> 10:10.425
No.

10:10.426 --> 10:12.460
Because if you want to talk
to me, then, please...

10:12.461 --> 10:14.761
Why can't you just back me up on this?

10:21.970 --> 10:24.371
Okay.

10:26.374 --> 10:27.642
I'll tell you what.

10:27.643 --> 10:28.877
I will call Diplomatic Security

10:28.878 --> 10:31.279
and have them send me over
a couple of candidates.

10:31.280 --> 10:33.014
How's that?

10:33.015 --> 10:35.415
Thank you.

10:37.752 --> 10:42.122
I have to get back to work,
so I'll see you tonight.

